        <h1 class="pg-title">Augustus Caesar</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">The emperor who copied his uncle and wrote his own name into the calendar too</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        The month of August on the Gregorian calendar is named after another man — <strong>Augustus Caesar</strong>, the first emperor of Rome. The month was originally called <em>Sextilis</em>, the Latin word for "sixth," because it was the sixth month of the Roman year. Augustus, watching what his uncle Julius had done a generation earlier, decided his name belonged on a month too. The renaming stuck. It has been "August" ever since.
      </p>

      <h2>Who He Was</h2>

      <p>
        Augustus Caesar — born Gaius Octavius, later called Octavian — was the great-nephew and adopted son of Julius Caesar. After Julius was assassinated in 44 BC, Octavian fought a long civil war against Mark Antony and Cleopatra, eventually emerging as sole ruler of Rome. The Senate gave him the title <em>Augustus</em> ("the revered one") in 27 BC, and he ruled as Rome's first emperor until his death in AD 14.
      </p>

      <p>
        His reign was long, prosperous, and well-managed by Roman standards — but it was also the reign during which Yahushua the Messiah was born. Luke 2:1 names him directly: <em>"And it came to pass in those days, that there went out a decree from Caesar Augustus, that all the world should be taxed."</em> The very decree that brought Joseph and Mary to Bethlehem was an act of Augustus's administration.
      </p>

      <p>
        Augustus saw what Julius had done with <em>Quintilis</em> — renaming it July after himself — and decided to do the same with <em>Sextilis</em>. He chose this month because it was the month in which several of his greatest victories had occurred (including the conquest of Egypt). The senate approved the renaming. <em>Augustus</em> — the month of Augustus — became August.
      </p>

      <p>
        There is a small but telling detail. The original <em>Sextilis</em> had 30 days, while Julius's renamed July had 31. Augustus, refusing to let his month be shorter than his uncle's, took a day from February and added it to August so the two months would be equal. That is why February has only 28 days (or 29 in a leap year) today: an emperor's vanity stole a day from it two thousand years ago, and the calendar still bears the wound.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        There is no pagan god in this story either. There is just another man — a more powerful man than even Julius — who looked at his uncle's vanity and decided he wanted the same. So he took a month, put his name on it, stole a day from another month to make sure his was as long as Julius's, and called it done. The calendar that Yahuah's people use every day still preserves all of it.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Daniel 4:30–31</span> — "The king spake, and said, Is not this great Babylon, that I have built for the house of the kingdom by the might of my power, and for the honour of my majesty? While the word was in the king's mouth, there fell a voice from heaven, saying, O king Nebuchadnezzar, to thee it is spoken; The kingdom is departed from thee."
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Isaiah 40:23</span> — "He bringeth the princes to nothing; he maketh the judges of the earth as vanity."
      </div>

      <p>
        Augustus considered himself <em>the revered one</em>. The Roman senate confirmed the title. Coins were minted with his face. A month was named after him. And yet — he died like every other man, his empire eventually fell, and the only reason most readers today have heard his name at all is that one decree of his sent Joseph and Mary to Bethlehem so that Yahushua could be born where Micah had said he would be born.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>The man who put his name on a month was, without knowing it, an instrument used by the One who sets the appointed times.</strong> Augustus's decree was not what brought the Messiah into the world. Yahuah's plan was. The decree was just the means. The vanity carved into the calendar still stands, but the One it tried to compete with had already decided how the story would unfold.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Some will ask: <em>"What month in Yahuah's calendar is August really?"</em> The question is misplaced.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's months are counted from the new moon. The first month — Aviv — begins when Spica meets the moon at the new moon nearest the spring equinox. Every month after that begins the day after the visible new-moon sliver appears. The months are numbered. <strong>Their start dates do not line up with the Roman months — and they shift slightly from one year to the next.</strong>
      </p>

      <p>
        What we call "August" on the Roman calendar will overlap with parts of two different months on Yahuah's calendar — and which two depends on the year. To say "August is really Month X" is to commit the same error as saying "Christ died on Friday." It mixes Babylon's clock with Yahuah's clock, when the two were never meant to translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        The eighth month of the modern calendar is named after a Roman emperor who copied his uncle's self-promotion. The fact that February is short and August is long is a fingerprint of imperial ego — a day stolen, a month lengthened, a name preserved. Most who say "August" have no idea. They assume it just means "summer month" or vaguely "imposing." It does not. It means <em>the revered one</em> — and the man it refers to has been dead for two thousand years.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>The Roman calendar is the calendar of dead emperors and pagan gods.</strong> Yahuah's calendar is the calendar of the heavens — set in motion on the fourth day of creation, kept by the new moon and the stars, untouched by any senator's vote or emperor's pen.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> His months are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the name an emperor wrote onto his own victory month. The faithful watch the heavens. The world watches the leftover fingerprints of Roman vanity. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        August is Augustus's month — copied from his uncle, lengthened by a day stolen from February, named for an emperor who called himself "the revered one." The heavens know nothing about him. They keep time the way Yahuah designed them, and no emperor has ever moved the new moon.
      </div>

